{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Broken swap invariant allows draining nearly an entire reserve for dust-sized input","locations":["0x8ce2f9286f50fbe2464bfd881fab8effc8dc584f/contracts/SwaposV2Pair.sol:180","0x8ce2f9286f50fbe2464bfd881fab8effc8dc584f/contracts/SwaposV2Pair.sol:181","0x8ce2f9286f50fbe2464bfd881fab8effc8dc584f/contracts/SwaposV2Pair.sol:182"],"claim":"`swap()` computes post-swap balances on a 10,000-based scale and subtracts a 0.1% fee via `amountIn * 10`, but it still compares the result against `_reserve0 * _reserve1 * 1000**2` instead of `10000**2`. The invariant check is therefore 100x too weak and accepts massively undercollateralized swaps.","impact":"Any attacker can permissionlessly steal almost all of either reserve with only a dust input, directly draining LP funds and rendering the pool price state meaningless.","paths":["If reserves are `(R0,R1)`, an attacker can pre-send 1 wei of `token0` and call `swap(0, R1-1, attacker, \"\")`; `amount0In > 0` and the weakened K-check still passes.","The attack is symmetric for `token0` by pre-paying a dust amount of `token1` and requesting nearly all of `reserve0` as output."] ,"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Low","confidence":"low","title":"Pair token bindings remain mutable if the factory ever re-calls `initialize()`","locations":["0x8ce2f9286f50fbe2464bfd881fab8effc8dc584f/contracts/SwaposV2Pair.sol:65","0x8ce2f9286f50fbe2464bfd881fab8effc8dc584f/contracts/SwaposV2Pair.sol:66","0x8ce2f9286f50fbe2464bfd881fab8effc8dc584f/contracts/SwaposV2Pair.sol:67","0x8ce2f9286f50fbe2464bfd881fab8effc8dc584f/contracts/SwaposV2Pair.sol:68","0x8ce2f9286f50fbe2464bfd881fab8effc8dc584f/contracts/SwaposV2Pair.sol:69"],"claim":"`initialize()` only checks `msg.sender == factory` and never records that initialization has already happened. A later factory call can overwrite `token0` and `token1` for an already funded pair.","impact":"If the factory later gains an unintended arbitrary-call path, is upgraded unsafely, or is otherwise misused, existing pools can be rebound to attacker-chosen token addresses. The pair would then mint, burn, swap, skim, and sync against the wrong assets, potentially orphaning the real reserves and bricking redemptions.","paths":["Users deposit liquidity into a legitimate pair.","At a later time, the factory invokes `initialize()` again with different token addresses.","Subsequent pair operations reference the new token contracts, while the original underlying tokens remain stranded in the pair address."] ,"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Protocol fee formula over-mints LP shares to `feeTo`","source_agents":["codex_1"],"reason":"The code explicitly documents a `1/2th` sqrt(k) fee at line 88 and the implementation matches that comment. Without contrary protocol specs, this is an economic design choice rather than a demonstrated vulnerability."},{"title":"Division by Zero in Price Oracle Calculation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`_update()` only calls `uqdiv()` inside `if (timeElapsed > 0 && _reserve0 != 0 && _reserve1 != 0)`, so zero reserves do not trigger division by zero."},{"title":"Unprotected skim Function Allows Anyone to Drain Excess Tokens","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`skim()` only transfers balances above the recorded reserves. This is standard Uniswap V2 behavior for recovering accidental excess tokens and does not let callers drain accounted LP reserves."},{"title":"Unprotected sync Function Allows Reserve Manipulation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`sync()` merely updates reserves to actual token balances. Any reserve change requires the caller to first move real tokens into the pair, so this is standard spot-price/oracle manipulation, not a standalone pair vulnerability."},{"title":"IERC20 Interface Incompatibility with Non-Standard ERC20 Tokens","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The provided pair code only uses `balanceOf` and transfer-style calls; it never calls `name()`, `symbol()`, or `decimals()` on the underlying tokens. The optional metadata declarations in `IERC20` are inert here."},{"title":"Missing Zero Address Validation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Only the factory can set `token0`/`token1`, so zero-address initialization is a trusted-factory misuse case. Zero-address approval/transfer behavior on the LP token does not create third-party theft or protocol-level breakage."},{"title":"K Check Uses Integer Division Losing Precision","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The report misdiagnoses the issue. The real problem is the 10000-vs-1000 scaling mismatch in the invariant constant, not ordinary integer precision loss."},{"title":"Permit Function Allows Exact Deadline Timestamp","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`deadline >= block.timestamp` is standard permit semantics and does not create meaningful exploitability."},{"title":"Swap Callback Allows Arbitrary Data Execution","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The callback is the intended flash-swap hook. Reentrancy into pair state is blocked by `lock`, and no invariant bypass beyond the separate K-check bug is shown."},{"title":"Fee On/Off Logic Can Leave Stale kLast Value","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Resetting `kLast` to zero when fees are off is standard Uniswap V2 behavior; re-enabling fees starts a new accounting baseline rather than creating an over-minting bug by itself."}]}
